SIMPLE: woe
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Woe
<hw>Woe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>wo</ets>,
<ets>wa</ets>, woo, AS. <ets>w⟦amac⟧</ets>, interj.; akin to D.
<ets>wee</ets>, OS. & OHG. <ets>w⟦emac⟧</ets>, G. <ets>weh</ets>, Icel.
<ets>vei</ets>, Dan. <ets>vee</ets>, Sw. <ets>ve</ets>, Goth.
<ets>wai</ets>; cf. L. <ets>vae</ets>, Gr. <?/. ⟦root⟧128. Cf.
<er>Wail</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Formerly written also
<asp>wo</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Grief; sorrow; misery; heavy calamity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus saying, from her side the fatal key,⟦br⟧
Sad instrument of all our <qex>woe</qex>, she took.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[They] weep each other's <qex>woe</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A curse; a malediction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Can there be a <qex>woe</qex> or curse in all the stores of
vengeance equal to the malignity of such a practice?</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Woe</xex> is used in denunciation, and in
exclamations of sorrow. ⟦ldquo⟧ <xex>Woe</xex> is me! for I am
undone.⟦rdquo⟧</note> <rj><au>Isa. vi. 5.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O! <qex>woe</qex> were us alive [i.e., in life].</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Woe</qex> unto him that striveth with his Maker!</q>
<rj><qau>Isa. xlv. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Woe worth</b></col>, <cd>Woe be to. See <er>Worth</er>,
<pos>v. i.</pos></cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Woe worth</qex> the chase, <qex>woe worth</qex> the day,⟦br⟧
That costs thy life, my gallant gray!</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Woe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Woe
<hw>Woe</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Woeful; sorrowful.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His clerk was <qex>woe</qex> to do that deed.</q> <rj><qau>Robert
of Brunne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Woe</qex> was this knight and sorrowfully he sighed.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And looking up he waxed wondrous <qex>woe</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Woe-begone</ent>⟦br⟧
